# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: geolocation-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] The **`Geolocation`** interface represents an object able to obtain the position of the device programmatically.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] It gives Web content access to the location of the device.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] This allows a website or app to offer customized results based on the user's location.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] An object with this interface is obtained using the `navigator.geolocation` property implemented by the `Navigator` object.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] Determines the device's current location and gives back a `GeolocationPosition` object with the data.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] Returns a `long` value representing the newly established callback function to be invoked whenever the device location changes.
[src:geolocation-api/api-geolocation] Removes the particular handler previously installed using `watchPosition()`.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The **Geolocation API** allows the user to provide their location to web applications if they so desire.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] For privacy reasons, the user is asked for permission to report location information.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] WebExtensions that wish to use the `Geolocation` object must add the `"geolocation"` permission to their manifest.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The user's operating system will prompt the user to allow location access the first time it is requested.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] You will often want to retrieve a user's location information in your web app, for example to plot their location on a map, or display personalized information relevant to their location.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The Geolocation API is accessed via a call to `navigator.geolocation`; this will cause the user's browser to ask them for permission to access their location data.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] If they accept, then the browser will use the best available functionality on the device to access this information (for example, GPS).
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] For further information on Geolocation usage, read Using the Geolocation API.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The main class of this API — contains methods to retrieve the user's current position, watch for changes in their position, and clear a previously-set watch.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] A `GeolocationPosition` instance is returned by a successful call to one of the methods contained inside `Geolocation`, inside a success callback, and contains a timestamp plus a `GeolocationCoordinates` object instance.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] Represents the coordinates of a user's position; a `GeolocationCoordinates` instance contains latitude, longitude, and other important related information.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] A `GeolocationPositionError` is returned by an unsuccessful call to one of the methods contained inside `Geolocation`, inside an error callback, and contains an error code and message.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] Returns a `Geolocation` object instance, from which all other functionality can be accessed.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The Geolocation API allows users to programmatically access location information in secure contexts.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] Access may further be controlled by the Permissions Policy directive `geolocation`.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The default allowlist for `geolocation` is `self`, which allows access to location information in same-origin nested frames only.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] Geolocation data may reveal information that the device owner does not want to share.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] Therefore, users must grant explicit permission via a prompt when either `Geolocation.getCurrentPosition()` or `Geolocation.watchPosition()` is called (unless the permission state is already `granted` or `denied`).
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The lifetime of a granted permission depends on the user agent, and may be time based, session based, or even permanent.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] The Permissions API `geolocation` permission can be used to test whether access to use location information is `granted`, `denied` or `prompt` (requires user acknowledgement of a prompt).
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] See Using the Geolocation API for example code.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] As Wi-Fi-based locating is often provided by Google, the vanilla Geolocation API may be unavailable in China.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] You may use local third-party providers such as Baidu, Autonavi, or Tencent.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation-api] These services use the user's IP address and/or a local app to provide enhanced positioning.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Geopositioning uses various visual and electronic methods including position lines and position circles, celestial navigation, radio navigation, radio and WiFi positioning systems, and the use of satellite navigation systems.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The calculation requires measurements or observations of distances or angles to reference points whose positions are known.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] In 2D surveys, observations of three reference points are enough to compute a position in a two-dimensional plane.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] In practice, observations are subject to errors resulting from various physical and atmospheric factors that influence the measurement of distances and angles.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] A practical example of obtaining a position fix would be for a ship to take bearing measurements on three lighthouses positioned along the coast.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] These measurements could be made visually using a hand bearing compass, or in case of poor visibility, electronically using radar or radio direction finding.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Since all physical observations are subject to errors, the resulting position fix is also subject to inaccuracy.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Although in theory two lines of position (LOP) are enough to define a point, in practice 'crossing' more LOPs provides greater accuracy and confidence, especially if the lines cross at a good angle to each other.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Three LOPs are considered the minimum for a practical navigational fix.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The three LOPs when drawn on the chart will in general form a triangle, known as a 'cocked hat'.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The navigator will have more confidence in a position fix that is formed by a small cocked hat with angles close to those of an equilateral triangle.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The area of doubt surrounding a position fix is called an error ellipse.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] To minimize the error, electronic navigation systems generally use more than three reference points to compute a position fix to increase the data redundancy.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] As more redundant reference points are added, the position fix becomes more accurate and the area of the resulting error ellipse decreases.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The process of using 3 reference points to calculate the location is called Trilateration, and when using more than 3 points, *multilateration*.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Combining multiple observations to compute a position fix is equivalent to solving a system of linear equations.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Navigation systems use regression algorithms such as least squares in order to compute a position fix in 3D space.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] This is most commonly done by combining distance measurements to 4 or more GPS satellites, which orbit the Earth along known paths.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The result of position fixing is called a **position fix** (**PF**), or simply a **fix**, a position derived from measuring in relation to external reference points.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] In nautical navigation, the term is generally used with manual or visual techniques, such as the use of intersecting visual or radio position lines, rather than the use of more automated and accurate electronic methods like GPS; in aviation, use of electronic navigation aids is more common.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] A visual fix can be made by using any sighting device with a bearing indicator.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Two or more objects of known position are sighted, and the bearings recorded.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Bearing lines are then plotted on a chart through the locations of the sighted items.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The intersection of these lines is the current position of the vessel.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Usually, a fix is where two or more position lines intersect at any given time.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] If three position lines can be obtained, the resulting "cocked hat", where the three lines do not intersect at the same point, but create a triangle, gives the navigator an indication of the accuracy.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The most accurate fixes occur when the position lines are perpendicular to each other.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Fixes are a necessary aspect of navigation by dead reckoning, which relies on estimates of speed and course.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] The fix confirms the actual position during a journey.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] A fix can introduce inaccuracies if the reference point is not correctly identified or is inaccurately measured.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] Geopositioning can be referred to both global positioning and outdoor positioning, using for example GPS, and to indoor positioning, for all the situations where satellite GPS is not a viable option and the localization process has to happen indoors.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocation] For indoor positioning, tracking and localization there are many technologies that can be used, depending on the specific needs and on the environmental characteristics.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocationposition] It’s been available across browsers since July 2020.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocationposition] The **`GeolocationPosition`** interface represents the position of the concerned device at a given time.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocationposition] The position, represented by a `GeolocationCoordinates` object, comprehends the 2D position of the device, on a spheroid representing the Earth, but also its altitude and its speed.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocationposition] Returns a `GeolocationCoordinates` object defining the current location.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocationposition] Returns a timestamp, given as Unix time in milliseconds, representing the time at which the location was retrieved.
[src:geolocation-api/geolocationposition] Returns a JSON representation of the `GeolocationPosition` object and enables serialization with `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] The **`getCurrentPosition()`** method of the `Geolocation` interface is used to get the current position of the device.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] Note that in addition to requiring a secure context this feature may be blocked by the `geolocation` `Permissions-Policy`, and also requires that explicit permission be granted by the user.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] If required, the user will be prompted when this method is called.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] The permission state can be queried using the `geolocation` user permission in the Permissions API.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] A callback function that takes a `GeolocationPosition` object as its sole input parameter.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] An optional callback function that takes a `GeolocationPositionError` object as its sole input parameter.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] A positive `long` value indicating the maximum age in milliseconds of a possible cached position that is acceptable to return.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] If set to `0`, it means that the device cannot use a cached position and must attempt to retrieve the real current position.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] If set to `Infinity` the device must return a cached position regardless of its age.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] A positive `long` value representing the maximum length of time (in milliseconds) the device is allowed to take in order to return a position.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] The default value is `Infinity`, meaning that `getCurrentPosition()` won't return until the position is available.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] A boolean value that indicates the application would like to receive the best possible results.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] If `true` and if the device is able to provide a more accurate position, it will do so.
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] Note that this can result in slower response times or increased power consumption (with a GPS chip on a mobile device for example).
[src:geolocation-api/getcurrentposition] On the other hand, if `false`, the device can take the liberty to save resources by responding more quickly and/or using less power.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] officer operates the Global Positioning System in 2022.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The **Global Positioning System** (**GPS**) is a satellite-based hyperbolic navigation system owned by the United States Space Force and operated by Mission Delta 31.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It is one of the global navigation satellite systems (GNSS) that provide geolocation and time information to a GPS receiver anywhere on or near the Earth where signal quality permits.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It does not require the user to transmit any data, and operates independently of any telephone or Internet reception, though these technologies can enhance the usefulness of the GPS positioning information.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It provides critical positioning capabilities to military, civil, and commercial users around the world.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Although the United States government created, controls, and maintains GPS, it is freely accessible to anyone with a GPS receiver.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The prototype spacecraft was launched in 1978 and the full constellation of 24 satellites became operational in 1993.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As civilian GPS usage grew, there was increasing pressure to remove this error.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The SA system was temporarily disabled during the Gulf War, as a shortage of military GPS units meant that many US soldiers were using civilian GPS units sent from home.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In the 1990s, differential GPS systems from the US Coast Guard, Federal Aviation Administration, and similar agencies in other countries began to broadcast local GPS corrections, reducing the effect of both SA degradation and atmospheric effects (that military receivers also corrected for).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The U.S. military had also developed methods to perform local GPS jamming, meaning that the ability to globally degrade the system was no longer necessary.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As a result, United States President Bill Clinton signed a bill ordering that Selective Availability be disabled on May 1, 2000; and, in 2007, the US government announced that the next generation of GPS satellites would not include the feature.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Advances in technology and new demands on the existing system have led to efforts to modernize GPS and implement the next generation of GPS Block III satellites and Next Generation Operational Control System (OCX) which was authorized by the U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] When Selective Availability was discontinued, GPS was accurate to about 5 meters (16 ft).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS receivers that use the L5 band have much higher accuracy of 30 centimeters (12 in), while those for high-end applications such as engineering and land surveying are accurate to within 2 cm (3⁄4 in) and can even provide sub-millimeter accuracy with long-term measurements.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Consumer devices such as smartphones can be accurate to 4.9 m (16 ft) or better when used with assistive services like Wi-Fi positioning.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As of March 2026, 21 GPS satellites broadcast L5 signals, which are considered pre-operational prior to being broadcast by a full complement of 24 satellites in 2027.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS project was launched in the United States in 1973 to overcome the limitations of previous navigation systems, combining ideas from several predecessors, including classified engineering design studies from the 1960s.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Department of Defense developed the system, which originally used 24 satellites, for use by the United States military, and became fully operational in 1993.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Civilian use was allowed from the 1980s.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Easton of the Naval Research Laboratory, Ivan A.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Getting of The Aerospace Corporation, and Bradford Parkinson of the Applied Physics Laboratory are credited with inventing it.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The work of Gladys West of the Ballistic Sciences Branch at Dahlgren Naval Proving Ground on the creation of the mathematical geodetic Earth model is credited as instrumental in the development of computational techniques for detecting satellite positions with the precision needed for GPS.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The design of GPS is based partly on similar ground-based radio-navigation systems, such as LORAN and the Decca Navigator System, developed in the early 1940s.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1955, Friedwardt Winterberg proposed a test of general relativity—detecting time slowing in a strong gravitational field using accurate atomic clocks placed in orbit inside artificial satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Special and general relativity predicted that the clocks on GPS satellites, as observed by those on Earth, run 38 microseconds faster per day than those on the Earth.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The design of GPS corrects for this difference.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] When the Soviet Union launched its first artificial satellite (Sputnik 1) in 1957, two American physicists, William Guier and George Weiffenbach, at Johns Hopkins University's Applied Physics Laboratory (APL) monitored its radio transmissions.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Within hours they realized that, because of the Doppler effect, they could pinpoint where the satellite was along its orbit.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The Director of the APL gave them access to their UNIVAC I computer to perform the heavy calculations required.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Early the next year, Frank McClure, the deputy director of the APL, asked Guier and Weiffenbach to investigate the inverse problem: pinpointing the user's location, given the satellite's.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] (At the time, the Navy was developing the submarine-launched Polaris missile, which required them to know the submarine's location.) This led them and APL to develop the TRANSIT system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1959, ARPA (renamed DARPA in 1972) also played a role in TRANSIT.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] TRANSIT was first successfully tested in 1960.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It used a constellation of five satellites and could provide a navigational fix approximately once per hour.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Navy developed the Timation satellite, which proved the feasibility of placing accurate clocks in space, a technology required for GPS.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In the 1970s, the ground-based OMEGA navigation system, based on phase comparison of signal transmission from pairs of stations, became the first worldwide radio navigation system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Limitations of these systems drove the need for a more universal navigation solution with greater accuracy.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Although there were wide needs for accurate navigation in military and civilian sectors, almost none of those was seen as justification for the billions of dollars it would cost in research, development, deployment, and operation of a constellation of navigation satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] During the Cold War arms race, the nuclear threat to the existence of the United States was the one need that did justify this cost in the view of the United States Congress.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] This deterrent effect is why GPS was funded.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It is also the reason for the ultra-secrecy at that time.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The nuclear triad consisted of the United States Navy's submarine-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs) along with United States Air Force (USAF) strategic bombers and intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Considered vital to the nuclear deterrence posture, accurate determination of the SLBM launch position was a force multiplier.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Precise navigation would enable United States ballistic missile submarines to get an accurate fix of their positions before they launched their SLBMs.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The USAF, with two-thirds of the nuclear triad, also had requirements for a more accurate and reliable navigation system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force were developing their own technologies in parallel to solve what was essentially the same problem.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] To increase the survivability of ICBMs, there was a proposal to use mobile launch platforms (comparable to the Soviet SS-24 and SS-25) and so the need to fix the launch position had similarity to the SLBM situation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1960, the Air Force proposed a radio-navigation system called MOSAIC (Mobile System for Accurate ICBM Control) that was essentially a 3-D LORAN System.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] A follow-on study, Project 57, was performed in 1963 and it was "in this study that the GPS concept was born".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] That same year, the concept was pursued as Project 621B, which had "many of the attributes that you now see in GPS" and promised increased accuracy for U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Updates from the Navy TRANSIT system were too slow for the high speeds of Air Force operation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) continued making advances with their Timation (Time Navigation) satellites, first launched in 1967, second launched in 1969, with the third in 1974 carrying the first atomic clock into orbit and the fourth launched in 1977.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Another important predecessor to GPS came from a different branch of the United States military.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1964, the United States Army orbited its first Sequential Collation of Range (SECOR) satellite used for geodetic surveying.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The SECOR system included three ground-based transmitters at known locations that would send signals to the satellite transponder in orbit.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] A fourth ground-based station, at an undetermined position, could then use those signals to fix its location precisely.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The last SECOR satellite was launched in 1969.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] With these parallel developments in the 1960s, a superior system could be developed by synthesizing the best technologies from 621B, Transit, Timation, and SECOR in a multi-service program.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Satellite orbital position errors, induced by variations in the gravity field and radar refraction among others, had to be resolved.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Jury of Pan Am Aerospace Division in Florida from 1970 to 1973, used real-time data assimilation and recursive estimation to do so, reducing systematic and residual errors to a manageable level to permit accurate navigation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] During Labor Day weekend in 1973, a meeting of about twelve military officers at the Pentagon discussed the creation of a *Defense Navigation Satellite System (DNSS)*.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It was at this meeting that the real synthesis that became GPS was created.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Later that year, the DNSS program was named *Navstar.* The name *Navstar* was not an acronym, but was chosen simply as a nice-sounding word.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] With the individual satellites being associated with the name Navstar (as with the predecessors Transit and Timation), a more fully encompassing name was used to identify the constellation of Navstar satellites, *Navstar-GPS*.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Ten "Block I" prototype satellites were launched between 1978 and 1985 (an additional unit was destroyed in a launch failure).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The effect of the ionosphere on radio transmission was investigated in a geophysics laboratory of Air Force Cambridge Research Laboratory, renamed to Air Force Geophysical Research Lab (AFGRL) in 1974.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] AFGRL developed the Klobuchar model for computing ionospheric corrections to GPS location.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Of note is work done by Australian space scientist Elizabeth Essex-Cohen at AFGRL in 1974.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] She was concerned with the curving of the paths of radio waves (atmospheric refraction) traversing the ionosphere from Navstar satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The first Block II satellite was launched on February 14, 1989, and the 24th satellite was launched in 1994.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS program cost at this point, not including the cost of the user equipment but including the costs of the satellite launches, has been estimated at US$5 billion (equivalent to $11 billion in 2025).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Initially, the highest-quality signal was reserved for military use, and the signal available for civilian use was intentionally degraded, in a policy known as Selective Availability.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] President Bill Clinton signing a policy directive to turn off Selective Availability to provide the same accuracy to civilians that was afforded to the military.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Secretary of Defense, William Perry, in view of the widespread growth of differential GPS services by private industry to improve civilian accuracy.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Moreover, the U.S. military was developing technologies to deny GPS service to potential adversaries on a regional basis.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Selective Availability was removed from the GPS architecture beginning with GPS-III.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Since its deployment, the U.S. has implemented several improvements to the GPS service, including new signals for civil use and increased accuracy and integrity for all users, all the while maintaining compatibility with existing GPS equipment.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Modernization of the satellite system has been an ongoing initiative by the U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Department of Defense through a series of satellite acquisitions to meet the growing needs of the military, civilians, and the commercial market.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As of early 2015, high-quality Standard Positioning Service (SPS) GPS receivers provided horizontal accuracy of better than 3.5 meters (11 ft), although many factors such as receiver and antenna quality and atmospheric issues can affect this accuracy.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS is owned and operated by the United States government as a national resource.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The Department of Defense is the steward of GPS.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The *Interagency GPS Executive Board (IGEB)* oversaw GPS policy matters from 1996 to 2004.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] After that, the National Space-Based Positioning, Navigation and Timing Executive Committee was established by presidential directive in 2004 to advise and coordinate federal departments and agencies on matters concerning the GPS and related systems.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The executive committee is chaired jointly by the Deputy Secretaries of Defense and Transportation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Its membership includes equivalent-level officials from the Departments of State, Commerce, and Homeland Security, the Joint Chiefs of Staff and NASA.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Components of the executive office of the president participate as observers to the executive committee, and the FCC chairman participates as a liaison.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] On February 10, 1993, the National Aeronautic Association selected the GPS Team as winners of the 1992 Robert J.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Collier Trophy, the US's most prestigious aviation award.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] This team combines researchers from the Naval Research Laboratory, the U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force, the Aerospace Corporation, Rockwell International Corporation, and IBM Federal Systems Company.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The citation honors them "for the most significant development for safe and efficient navigation and surveillance of air and spacecraft since the introduction of radio navigation 50 years ago".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Easton received the National Medal of Technology on February 13, 2006.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers Hall of Fame at Lackland A.F.B., San Antonio, Texas, March 2, 2010, for his role in space technology development and the engineering design concept of GPS conducted as part of Project 621B.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In 1998, GPS technology was inducted into the Space Foundation Space Technology Hall of Fame.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] On October 4, 2011, the International Astronautical Federation (IAF) awarded the Global Positioning System (GPS) its 60th Anniversary Award, nominated by IAF member, the American Institute for Aeronautics and Astronautics (AIAA).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The IAF Honors and Awards Committee recognized the uniqueness of the GPS program and the exemplary role it has played in building international collaboration for the benefit of humanity.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] On December 6, 2018, Gladys West was inducted into the Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers Hall of Fame in recognition of her work on an extremely accurate geodetic Earth model, which was ultimately used to determine the orbit of the GPS constellation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS satellites carry very stable atomic clocks that are synchronized with one another and with the reference atomic clocks at the ground control stations; any drift of the clocks aboard the satellites from the reference time maintained on the ground stations is corrected regularly.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Since the speed of radio waves (speed of light) is constant and independent of the satellite speed, the time delay between when the satellite transmits a signal and the ground station receives it is proportional to the distance from the satellite to the ground station.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] With the distance information collected from multiple ground stations, the location coordinates of any satellite at any time can be calculated with great precision.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Each GPS satellite carries an accurate record of its own position and time, and broadcasts that data continuously.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Conceptually, the receiver measures the TOAs (according to its own clock) of four satellite signals.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] From the TOAs and the TOTs, the receiver forms four time of flight (TOF) values, which are (given the speed of light) approximately equivalent to receiver-satellite ranges plus time difference between the receiver and GPS satellites multiplied by speed of light, which are called pseudo-ranges.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The receiver then computes its three-dimensional position and clock deviation from the four TOFs.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In practice the receiver position (in three dimensional Cartesian coordinates with origin at the Earth's center) and the offset of the receiver clock relative to the GPS time are computed simultaneously, using the navigation equations to process the TOFs.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The receiver's Earth-centered solution location is usually converted to latitude, longitude and height relative to an ellipsoidal Earth model.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The height may then be further converted to height relative to the geoid, which is essentially mean sea level.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] These coordinates may be displayed, such as on a moving map display, or recorded or used by some other system, such as a vehicle guidance system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As of 2025, these core principles are being enhanced by the ongoing modernization of the GPS constellation with the introduction of GPS III and GPS IIIF satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] These next-generation satellites feature more advanced atomic clocks for even greater timekeeping accuracy and broadcast more powerful, secure, and interoperable signals (such as L1C, L2C, and L5).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] This improves the precision of the time-of-flight (TOF) measurements and provides better resistance to signal interference, enhancing the reliability of the position calculation for all users.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Although usually not formed explicitly in the receiver processing, the conceptual time differences of arrival (TDOAs) define the measurement geometry.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Each TDOA corresponds to a hyperboloid of revolution (see Multilateration).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The line connecting the two satellites involved (and its extensions) forms the axis of the hyperboloid.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The receiver is located at the point where three hyperboloids intersect.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It is sometimes incorrectly said that the user location is at the intersection of three spheres.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] While simpler to visualize, this is the case only if the receiver has a clock synchronized with the satellite clocks (i.e., the receiver measures true ranges to the satellites rather than range differences).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] There are marked performance benefits to the user carrying a clock synchronized with the satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Foremost is that only three satellites are needed to compute a position solution.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] If it were an essential part of the GPS concept that all users needed to carry a synchronized clock, a smaller number of satellites could be deployed, but the cost and complexity of the user equipment would increase.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The description above is representative of a receiver start-up situation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Most receivers have a track algorithm, sometimes called a *tracker*, that combines sets of satellite measurements collected at different times—in effect, taking advantage of the fact that successive receiver positions are usually close to each other.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] After a set of measurements is processed, the tracker predicts the receiver location corresponding to the next set of satellite measurements.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] When the new measurements are collected, the receiver uses a weighting scheme to combine the new measurements with the tracker prediction.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In general, a tracker can (a) improve receiver position and time accuracy, (b) reject bad measurements, and (c) estimate receiver speed and direction.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The disadvantage of a tracker is that changes in speed or direction can be computed only with a delay, and that derived direction becomes inaccurate when the distance traveled between two position measurements drops below or near the random error of position measurement.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS units can use measurements of the Doppler shift of the signals received to compute velocity accurately.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] More advanced navigation systems use additional sensors like a compass or an inertial navigation system to complement GPS.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS requires four or more satellites to be visible for accurate navigation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The solution of the navigation equations gives the position of the receiver along with the difference between the time kept by the receiver's on-board clock and the true time-of-day, thereby eliminating the need for a more precise and possibly impractical receiver based clock.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Applications for GPS such as time transfer, traffic signal timing, and synchronization of cell phone base stations, make use of this cheap and highly accurate timing.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Some GPS applications use this time for display, or, other than for the basic position calculations, do not use it at all.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Although four satellites are required for normal operation, fewer apply in special cases.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] If one variable is already known, a receiver can determine its position using only three satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] For example, a ship on the open ocean usually has a known elevation close to 0 m, and the elevation of an aircraft may be known.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Some GPS receivers may use additional clues or assumptions such as reusing the last known altitude, dead reckoning, inertial navigation, or including information from the vehicle computer, to give a (possibly degraded) position when fewer than four satellites are visible.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The current GPS consists of three major segments.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] These are the space segment, a control segment, and a user segment.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Space Force develops, maintains, and operates the space and control segments.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS satellites broadcast signals from space, and each GPS receiver uses these signals to calculate its three-dimensional location (latitude, longitude, and altitude) and the current time.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The space segment (SS) is composed of 24 to 32 satellites, or Space Vehicles (SV), in medium Earth orbit, and also includes the payload adapters to the boosters required to launch them into orbit.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS design originally called for 24 SVs, eight each in three approximately circular orbits, but this was modified to six orbital planes with four satellites each.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The six orbit planes have approximately 55° inclination (tilt relative to the Earth's equator) and are separated by 60° right ascension of the ascending node (angle along the equator from a reference point to the orbit's intersection).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The orbital period is one-half of a sidereal day, about 11 hours and 58 minutes, so that the satellites pass over the same locations or almost the same locations every day.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The orbits are arranged so that at least six satellites are always within line of sight from everywhere on the Earth's surface (see animation at right).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The result of this objective is that the four satellites are not evenly spaced (90°) apart within each orbit.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In general terms, the angular difference between satellites in each orbit is 30°, 105°, 120°, and 105° apart, which sum to 360°.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Orbiting at an altitude of approximately 20,200 km (12,600 mi); orbital radius of approximately 26,600 km (16,500 mi), each SV makes two complete orbits each sidereal day, repeating the same ground track each day.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] This was very helpful during development because even with only four satellites, correct alignment means all four are visible from one spot for a few hours each day.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] For military operations, the ground track repeat can be used to ensure good coverage in combat zones.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As of February 2019, there are 31 satellites in the GPS constellation, 27 of which are in use at a given time with the rest allocated as stand-bys.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] A 32nd was launched in 2018, but as of July 2019 is still in evaluation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] More decommissioned satellites are in orbit and available as spares.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The additional satellites improve the precision of GPS receiver calculations by providing redundant measurements.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] With the increased number of satellites, the constellation was changed to a nonuniform arrangement.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Such an arrangement was shown to improve accuracy but also improves reliability and availability of the system, relative to a uniform system, when multiple satellites fail.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] With the expanded constellation, nine satellites are usually visible at any time from any point on the Earth with a clear horizon, ensuring considerable redundancy over the minimum four satellites needed for a position.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The MCS can also access Satellite Control Network (SCN) ground antennas (for additional command and control capability) and NGA (National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency) monitor stations.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The flight paths of the satellites are tracked by dedicated U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Space Force monitoring stations in Hawaii, Kwajalein Atoll, Ascension Island, Diego Garcia, Colorado Springs, Colorado and Cape Canaveral, Florida, along with shared NGA monitor stations operated in England, Argentina, Ecuador, Bahrain, Australia and Washington, DC.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The tracking information is sent to the MCS at Schriever Space Force Base 25 km (16 mi) ESE of Colorado Springs, which is operated by the 2nd Space Operations Squadron (2 SOPS) of the U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Then 2 SOPS contacts each GPS satellite regularly with a navigational update using dedicated or shared (AFSCN) ground antennas (GPS dedicated ground antennas are located at Kwajalein, Ascension Island, Diego Garcia, and Cape Canaveral).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] These updates synchronize the atomic clocks on board the satellites to within a few nanoseconds of each other, and adjust the ephemeris of each satellite's internal orbital model.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The updates are created by a Kalman filter that uses inputs from the ground monitoring stations, space weather information, and various other inputs.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] When a satellite's orbit is being adjusted, the satellite is marked *unhealthy*, so receivers do not use it.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] After the maneuver, engineers track the new orbit from the ground, upload the new ephemeris, and mark the satellite healthy again.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The operation control segment (OCS) currently serves as the control segment of record.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It provides the operational capability that supports GPS users and keeps the GPS operational and performing within specification.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] OCS replaced the 1970s-era mainframe computer at Schriever Air Force Base in September 2007.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] After installation, the system helped enable upgrades and provide a foundation for a new security architecture that supported U.S. armed forces.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] OCS will continue to be the ground control system of record until the new segment, Next Generation GPS Operation Control System (OCX), is fully developed and functional.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Department of Defense has claimed that the new capabilities provided by OCX will be the cornerstone for enhancing GPS's mission capabilities, enabling U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Space Force to enhance GPS operational services to U.S. combat forces, civil partners and domestic and international users.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS OCX program also will reduce cost, schedule and technical risk.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] It is designed to provide 50% sustainment cost savings through efficient software architecture and Performance-Based Logistics.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In addition, GPS OCX is expected to cost millions of dollars less than the cost to upgrade OCS while providing four times the capability.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS OCX program represents a critical part of GPS modernization and provides information assurance improvements over the current GPS OCS program.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Air Force announced the completion of GPS OCX Preliminary Design Review and confirmed that the OCX program is ready for the next phase of development.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The GPS OCX program missed major milestones and pushed its launch into 2021, 5 years past the original deadline.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] According to the Government Accounting Office in 2019, the 2021 deadline looked shaky.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The project remained delayed in 2023, and was (as of June 2023) 73% over its original estimated budget.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In late 2023, Frank Calvelli, the assistant secretary of the Air Force for space acquisitions and integration, stated that the project was estimated to go live some time during the summer of 2024.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The US Space Force accepted delivery of OCX Blocks I and II from contractor RTX on July 1, 2025, over 8 years behind schedule and roughly $4 billion over budget due to its monolithic development and constant feature creep while in process.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] If current Government Accountability Office estimates hold, the new system will enter service in December 2025.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] OCX Block 3F is currently in development to enable command and control of GPS IIIF satellites, currently slated to begin launching in 2027.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] The user segment (US) is composed of hundreds of thousands of U.S. and allied military users of the secure GPS Precise Positioning Service, and tens of millions of civil, commercial and scientific users of the Standard Positioning Service.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] In general, GPS receivers are composed of an antenna, tuned to the frequencies transmitted by the satellites, receiver-processors, and a highly stable clock (often a crystal oscillator).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] They may also include a display for providing location and speed information to the user.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] GPS receivers may include an input for differential corrections, using the RTCM SC-104 format.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] This is typically in the form of an RS-232 port at 4,800 bit/s speed.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Data is actually sent at a much lower rate, which limits the accuracy of the signal sent using RTCM.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Receivers with internal DGPS receivers can outperform those using external RTCM data.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] As of 2006, even low-cost units commonly include Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS) receivers.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Many GPS receivers can relay position data to a PC or other device using the NMEA 0183 protocol.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Although this protocol is officially defined by the National Marine Electronics Association (NMEA), references to this protocol have been compiled from public records, allowing open source tools like gpsd to read the protocol without violating intellectual property laws.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Other proprietary protocols exist as well, such as the SiRF and MTK protocols.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p01] Receivers can interface with other devices using methods including a serial connection, USB, or Bluetooth.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] While originally a military project, GPS is considered a dual-use technology, meaning it has significant civilian applications as well.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS has become a widely deployed and useful tool for commerce, scientific uses, tracking, and surveillance.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS's accurate time facilitates everyday activities such as banking, mobile phone operations, and even the control of power grids by allowing well synchronized hand-off switching.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Many civilian applications use one or more of GPS's three basic components: absolute location, relative movement, and time transfer.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The U.S. government controls the export of some civilian receivers.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This rule applies even to otherwise purely civilian units that only receive the L1 frequency and the C/A (Coarse/Acquisition) code.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Disabling operation above these limits exempts the receiver from classification as a munition.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The rule refers to operation at both the target altitude and speed, but some receivers stop operating even when stationary.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This has caused problems with some amateur radio balloon launches that regularly reach 30 km (100,000 ft).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] These limits only apply to units or components exported from the United States.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] A growing trade in various components exists, including GPS units from other countries.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS type navigation was first used in war in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, before GPS was fully developed in 1995, to assist Coalition Forces to navigate and perform maneuvers in the war.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The war also demonstrated the vulnerability of GPS to being jammed, when Iraqi forces installed jamming devices on likely targets that emitted radio noise, disrupting reception of the weak GPS signal.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS's vulnerability to jamming is a threat that continues to grow as jamming equipment and experience grows.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS signals have been reported to have been jammed many times over the years for military purposes.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Russia seems to have several objectives for this approach, such as intimidating neighbors while undermining confidence in their reliance on American systems, promoting their GLONASS alternative, disrupting Western military exercises, and protecting assets from drones.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] China uses jamming to discourage US surveillance aircraft near the contested Spratly Islands.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] North Korea has mounted several major jamming operations near its border with South Korea and offshore, disrupting flights, shipping and fishing operations.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Iranian Armed Forces disrupted the civilian airliner plane Flight PS752's GPS when it shot down the aircraft.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In the Russo-Ukrainian War, GPS-guided munitions provided to Ukraine by NATO countries experienced significant failure rates as a result of Russian electronic warfare.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Excalibur artillery shells efficiency rate hitting targets dropped from 70% to 6% as Russia adapted its electronic warfare activities.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] While most clocks derive their time from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the atomic clocks on the satellites are set to *GPS time*.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The difference is that GPS time is not corrected to match the rotation of the Earth, so it does not contain new leap seconds or other corrections that are periodically added to UTC.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS time was set to match UTC in 1980, but has since diverged.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The lack of corrections means that GPS time remains at a constant offset with International Atomic Time (TAI) (TAI – GPS = 19 seconds).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Periodic corrections are performed to the on-board clocks to keep them synchronized with ground clocks.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS navigation message includes the difference between GPS time and UTC.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] As of January 2017, GPS time is 18 seconds ahead of UTC because of the leap second added to UTC on December 31, 2016.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Receivers subtract this offset from GPS time to calculate UTC and specific time zone values.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] New GPS units may not show the correct UTC time until after receiving the UTC offset message.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS-UTC offset field can accommodate 255 leap seconds (eight bits).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS time is theoretically accurate to about 14 nanoseconds, due to the clock drift relative to International Atomic Time that the atomic clocks in GPS transmitters experience.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Most receivers lose some accuracy in their interpretation of the signals and are only accurate to about 100 nanoseconds.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS implements two major corrections to its time signals for relativistic effects: one for relative velocity of satellite and receiver, using the special theory of relativity, and one for the difference in gravitational potential between satellite and receiver, using general relativity.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The acceleration of the satellite could also be computed independently as a correction, depending on purpose, but normally the effect is already dealt with in the first two corrections.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] As opposed to the year, month, and day format of the Gregorian calendar, the GPS date is expressed as a week number and a seconds-into-week number.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The week number is transmitted as a ten-bit field in the C/A and P(Y) navigation messages, and so it becomes zero again every 1,024 weeks (19.6 years).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] It happened the second time at 23:59:42 UTC on April 6, 2019.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] To determine the current Gregorian date, a GPS receiver must be provided with the approximate date (to within 3,584 days) to correctly translate the GPS date signal.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] To address this concern in the future the modernized GPS civil navigation (CNAV) message uses a 13-bit field that only repeats every 8,192 weeks (157 years), thus lasting until 2137 (157 years after GPS week zero).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The navigational signals transmitted by GPS satellites encode a variety of information including satellite positions, the state of the internal clocks, and the health of the network.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] These signals are transmitted on two separate carrier frequencies that are common to all satellites in the network.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Two different encodings are used: a public encoding that enables lower resolution navigation, and an encrypted encoding used by the U.S. military.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Each GPS satellite continuously broadcasts a *navigation message* on L1 (C/A and P/Y) and L2 (P/Y) frequencies at a rate of 50 bits per second (see bitrate).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Each complete message takes 750 seconds (12+1⁄2 minutes) to complete.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The message structure has a basic format of a 1500-bit-long frame made up of five subframes, each subframe being 300 bits (6 seconds) long.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Subframes 4 and 5 are subcommutated 25 times each, so that a complete data message requires the transmission of 25 full frames.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Each subframe consists of ten words, each 30 bits long.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Thus, with 300 bits in a subframe times 5 subframes in a frame times 25 frames in a message, each message is 37,500 bits long.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] At a transmission rate of 50-bit/s, this gives 750 seconds to transmit an entire almanac message (GPS).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Each 30-second frame begins precisely on the minute or half-minute as indicated by the atomic clock on each satellite.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The first subframe of each frame encodes the week number and the time within the week, as well as the data about the health of the satellite.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The second and the third subframes contain the *ephemeris* – the precise orbital parameters for the satellite.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The fourth and fifth subframes contain the *almanac*, which contains coarse orbit and status information for up to 32 satellites in the constellation as well as data related to error correction.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Thus, to obtain an accurate satellite location from this transmitted message, the receiver must demodulate the message from each satellite it includes in its solution for 18 to 30 seconds.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] To collect all transmitted almanacs, the receiver must demodulate the message for 732 to 750 seconds or 12+1⁄2 minutes.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same frequencies, encoding signals using unique code-division multiple access (CDMA) so receivers can distinguish individual satellites from each other.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The system uses two distinct CDMA encoding types: the coarse/acquisition (C/A) code, which is accessible by the general public, and the precise (P(Y)) code, which is encrypted so that only the U.S. military and other NATO nations who have been given access to the encryption code can access it.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The ephemeris is updated every 2 hours and is sufficiently stable for 4 hours, with provisions for updates every 6 hours or longer in non-nominal conditions.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The almanac is updated typically every 24 hours.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Additionally, data for a few weeks following is uploaded in case of transmission updates that delay data upload.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same two frequencies, 1.57542 GHz (L1 signal) and 1.2276 GHz (L2 signal).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The satellite network uses a CDMA spread-spectrum technique where the low-bitrate message data is encoded with a high-rate pseudo-random (PRN) sequence that is different for each satellite.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver must be aware of the PRN codes for each satellite to reconstruct the actual message data.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The C/A code, for civilian use, transmits data at 1.023 million chips per second, whereas the P code, for U.S. military use, transmits at 10.23 million chips per second.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The actual internal reference of the satellites is 10.22999999543 MHz to compensate for relativistic effects that make observers on the Earth perceive a different time reference with respect to the transmitters in orbit.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The L1 carrier is modulated by both the C/A and P codes, while the L2 carrier is only modulated by the P code.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The P code can be encrypted as a so-called P(Y) code that is only available to military equipment with a proper decryption key.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Both the C/A and P(Y) codes impart the precise time-of-day to the user.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The L3 signal at a frequency of 1.38105 GHz is used to transmit data from the satellites to ground stations.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This data is used by the United States Nuclear Detonation (NUDET) Detection System (USNDS) to detect, locate, and report nuclear detonations (NUDETs) in the Earth's atmosphere and near space.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] One usage is the enforcement of nuclear test ban treaties.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The L4 band at 1.379913 GHz is being studied for additional ionospheric correction.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The L5 frequency band at 1.17645 GHz was added in the process of GPS modernization.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This frequency falls into an internationally protected range for aeronautical navigation, promising little or no interference under all circumstances.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The first Block IIF satellite that provides this signal was launched in May 2010.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] On February 5, 2016, the 12th and final Block IIF satellite was launched.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The L5 consists of two carrier components that are in phase quadrature with each other.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Each carrier component is bi-phase shift key (BPSK) modulated by a separate bit train.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In 2011, a conditional waiver was granted to LightSquared to operate a terrestrial broadband service near the L1 band.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS community had not objected to the LightSquared (formerly MSV and SkyTerra) applications until November 2010, when LightSquared applied for a modification to its Ancillary Terrestrial Component (ATC) authorization.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This filing (SAT-MOD-20101118-00239) amounted to a request to run several orders of magnitude more power in the same frequency band for terrestrial base stations, essentially repurposing what was supposed to be a "quiet neighborhood" for signals from space as the equivalent of a cellular network.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Testing in the first half of 2011 has demonstrated that the effects from the lower 10 MHz of spectrum are minimal to GPS devices (less than 1% of the total GPS devices are affected).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The upper 10 MHz intended for use by LightSquared may have some effect on GPS devices.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] There is some concern that this may seriously degrade the GPS signal for many consumer uses.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] *Aviation Week* magazine reports that the latest testing (June 2011) confirms "significant jamming" of GPS by LightSquared's system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Because all of the satellite signals are modulated onto the same L1 carrier frequency, the signals must be separated after demodulation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This is done by assigning each satellite a unique binary sequence known as a Gold code.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The signals are decoded after demodulation using addition of the Gold codes corresponding to the satellites monitored by the receiver.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] If the almanac information has previously been acquired, the receiver picks the satellites to listen for by their PRNs, unique numbers in the range 1 through 32.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] If the almanac information is not in memory, the receiver enters a search mode until a lock is obtained on one of the satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] To obtain a lock, it is necessary that there be an unobstructed line of sight from the receiver to the satellite.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver can then acquire the almanac and determine the satellites it should listen for.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] As it detects each satellite's signal, it identifies it by its distinct C/A code pattern.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] There can be a delay of up to 30 seconds before the first estimate of position because of the need to read the ephemeris data.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Processing of the navigation message enables the determination of the time of transmission and the satellite position at this time.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] For more information see Demodulation and Decoding, Advanced.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver uses messages received from satellites to determine the satellite positions and time sent.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The *x, y,* and *z* components of satellite position and the time sent (*s*) are designated as [*xi, yi, zi, si*] where the subscript *i* denotes the satellite and has the value 1, 2, ..., *n*, where *n* ≥ 4.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] When the time of message reception indicated by the on-board receiver clock is ${\tilde {t}}_{i}$ , the true reception time is $t_{i}={\tilde {t}}_{i}-b$ , where *b* is the receiver's clock bias from the much more accurate GPS clocks employed by the satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver clock bias is the same for all received satellite signals (assuming the satellite clocks are all perfectly synchronized).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The message's transit time is ${\tilde {t}}_{i}-b-s_{i}$ , where *si* is the satellite time.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Assuming the message traveled at the speed of light, *c*, the distance traveled is $\left({\tilde {t}}_{i}-b-s_{i}\right)c$ .
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Since the equations have four unknowns [*x, y, z, b*]—the three components of GPS receiver position and the clock bias—signals from at least four satellites are necessary to attempt solving these equations.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] They can be solved by algebraic or numerical methods.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Existence and uniqueness of GPS solutions are discussed by Abell and Chaffee.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] When *n* is greater than four, this system is overdetermined and a fitting method must be used.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The amount of error in the results varies with the received satellites' locations in the sky, since certain configurations (when the received satellites are close together in the sky) cause larger errors.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Receivers usually calculate a running estimate of the error in the calculated position.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This is done by multiplying the basic resolution of the receiver by quantities called the geometric dilution of position (GDOP) factors, calculated from the relative sky directions of the satellites used.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver location is expressed in a specific coordinate system, such as latitude and longitude using the WGS 84 geodetic datum or a country-specific system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS equations can be solved by numerical and analytical methods.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Geometrical interpretations can enhance the understanding of these solution methods.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The measured ranges, called pseudoranges, contain clock errors.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In a simplified idealization in which the ranges are synchronized, these true ranges represent the radii of spheres, each centered on one of the transmitting satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The solution for the position of the receiver is then at the intersection of the surfaces of these spheres; see trilateration (more generally, true-range multilateration).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Signals from at minimum three satellites are required, and their three spheres would typically intersect at two points.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] One of the points is the location of the receiver, and the other moves rapidly in successive measurements and would not usually be on Earth's surface.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In practice, there are many sources of inaccuracy besides clock bias, including random errors as well as the potential for precision loss from subtracting numbers close to each other if the centers of the spheres are relatively close together.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This means that the position calculated from three satellites alone is unlikely to be accurate enough.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Data from more satellites can help because of the tendency for random errors to cancel out and also by giving a larger spread between the sphere centers.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] But at the same time, more spheres will not generally intersect at one point.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Therefore, a near intersection gets computed, typically via least squares.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The more signals available, the better the approximation is likely to be.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] If the pseudorange between the receiver and satellite *i* and the pseudorange between the receiver and satellite *j* are subtracted, *pi* − *pj*, the common receiver clock bias (*b*) cancels out, resulting in a difference of distances *di* − *dj*.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The locus of points having a constant difference in distance to two points (here, two satellites) is a hyperbola on a plane and a hyperboloid of revolution (more specifically, a two-sheeted hyperboloid) in 3D space (see Multilateration).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Thus, from four pseudorange measurements, the receiver can be placed at the intersection of the surfaces of three hyperboloids each with foci at a pair of satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] With additional satellites, the multiple intersections are not necessarily unique, and a best-fitting solution is sought instead.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver position can be interpreted as the center of an inscribed sphere (insphere) of radius *bc*, given by the receiver clock bias *b* (scaled by the speed of light *c*).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The insphere location is such that it touches other spheres.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The circumscribing spheres are centered at the GPS satellites, whose radii equal the measured pseudoranges *p*i.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This configuration is distinct from the one described above, in which the spheres' radii were the unbiased or geometric ranges *d*i.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The clock in the receiver is usually not of the same quality as the ones in the satellites and will not be accurately synchronized to them.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This produces pseudoranges with large differences compared to the true distances to the satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Therefore, in practice, the time difference between the receiver clock and the satellite time is defined as an unknown clock bias *b*.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The equations are then solved simultaneously for the receiver position and the clock bias.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The solution space [*x, y, z, b*] can be seen as a four-dimensional spacetime, and signals from at minimum four satellites are needed.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In that case each of the equations describes a hypercone (or spherical cone), with the cusp located at the satellite, and the base a sphere around the satellite.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The receiver is at the intersection of four or more of such hypercones.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] When more than four satellites are available, the calculation can use the four best, or more than four simultaneously (up to all visible satellites), depending on the number of receiver channels, processing capability, and geometric dilution of precision (GDOP).
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Using more than four involves an over-determined system of equations with no unique solution; such a system can be solved by a least-squares or weighted least squares method.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Both the equations for four satellites, or the least squares equations for more than four, are non-linear and need special solution methods.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] A common approach is by iteration on a linearized form of the equations, such as the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The GPS was initially developed assuming use of a numerical least-squares solution method—i.e., before closed-form solutions were found.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] One closed-form solution to the above set of equations was developed by S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Its properties are well known; in particular, proponents claim it is superior in low-GDOP situations, compared to iterative least squares methods.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Bancroft's method is algebraic, as opposed to numerical, and can be used for four or more satellites.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] When four satellites are used, the key steps are inversion of a 4x4 matrix and solution of a single-variable quadratic equation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Bancroft's method provides one or two solutions for the unknown quantities.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] When there are two (usually the case), only one is a near-Earth sensible solution.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] When a receiver uses more than four satellites for a solution, Bancroft uses the generalized inverse (i.e., the pseudoinverse) to find a solution.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] A case has been made that iterative methods, such as the Gauss–Newton algorithm approach for solving over-determined non-linear least squares problems, generally provide more accurate solutions.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] (2015) states that "Bancroft's (1985) solution is a very early, if not the first, closed-form solution." Other closed-form solutions were published afterwards, although their adoption in practice is unclear.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS error analysis examines error sources in GPS results and the expected size of those errors.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS makes corrections for receiver clock errors and other effects, but some residual errors remain uncorrected.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Error sources include signal arrival time measurements, numerical calculations, atmospheric effects (ionospheric/tropospheric delays), ephemeris and clock data, multipath signals, and natural and artificial interference.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Magnitude of residual errors from these sources depends on geometric dilution of precision.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Artificial errors may result from jamming devices and threaten ships and aircraft or from intentional signal degradation through selective availability, which limited accuracy to ≈ 6–12 m (20–40 ft), but has been switched off since May 1, 2000.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GNSS enhancement refers to techniques used to improve the accuracy of positioning information provided by the Global Positioning System or other global navigation satellite systems in general, a network of satellites used for navigation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Enhancement methods of improving accuracy rely on external information being integrated into the calculation process.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] There are many such systems in place and they are generally named or described based on how the GPS sensor receives the information.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In the United States, GPS receivers are regulated under the Federal Communications Commission's (FCC) Part 15 rules.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] As indicated in the manuals of GPS-enabled devices sold in the United States, as a Part 15 device, it "must accept any interference received, including interference that may cause undesired operation".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] With respect to GPS devices in particular, the FCC states that GPS receiver manufacturers "must use receivers that reasonably discriminate against reception of signals outside their allocated spectrum".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] For the last 30 years, GPS receivers have operated next to the Mobile Satellite Service band, and have discriminated against reception of mobile satellite services, such as Inmarsat, without any issue.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The spectrum allocated for GPS L1 use by the FCC is 1559 to 1610 MHz, while the spectrum allocated for satellite-to-ground use owned by LightSquared is the Mobile Satellite Service band.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Since 1996, the FCC has authorized licensed use of the spectrum neighboring the GPS band of 1525 to 1559 MHz to the Virginia company LightSquared.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] On March 1, 2001, the FCC received an application from LightSquared's predecessor, Motient Services, to use their allocated frequencies for an integrated satellite-terrestrial service.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS Industry Council came to an out-of-band-emissions (OOBE) agreement with LightSquared to prevent transmissions from LightSquared's ground-based stations from emitting transmissions into the neighboring GPS band of 1559 to 1610 MHz.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] We do not intend, nor will we permit, the terrestrial component to become a stand-alone service." This authorization was reviewed and approved by the U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Interdepartment Radio Advisory Committee, which includes the U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Coast Guard, Federal Aviation Administration, National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), U.S.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The January 2011 order makes final authorization contingent upon studies of GPS interference issues carried out by a LightSquared led working group along with GPS industry and Federal agency participation.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] On February 14, 2012, the FCC initiated proceedings to vacate LightSquared's Conditional Waiver Order based on the NTIA's conclusion that there was currently no practical way to mitigate potential GPS interference.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] GPS receiver manufacturers design GPS receivers to use spectrum beyond the GPS-allocated band.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In some cases, GPS receivers are designed to use up to 400 MHz of spectrum in either direction of the L1 frequency of 1575.42 MHz, because mobile satellite services in those regions are broadcasting from space to ground, and at power levels commensurate with mobile satellite services.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] As regulated under the FCC's Part 15 rules, GPS receivers are not warranted protection from signals outside GPS-allocated spectrum.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] This is why GPS operates next to the Mobile Satellite Service band, and also why the Mobile Satellite Service band operates next to GPS.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The symbiotic relationship of spectrum allocation ensures that users of both bands are able to operate cooperatively and freely.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The FCC adopted rules in February 2003 that allowed Mobile Satellite Service (MSS) licensees such as LightSquared to construct a small number of ancillary ground-based towers in their licensed spectrum to "promote more efficient use of terrestrial wireless spectrum".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] MSS ATC is unlikely to compete directly with terrestrial CMRS for the same customer base...".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In 2004, the FCC clarified that the ground-based towers would be ancillary, noting: "We will authorize MSS ATC subject to conditions that ensure that the added terrestrial component remains ancillary to the principal MSS offering.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] To build public support of efforts to continue the 2004 FCC authorization of LightSquared's ancillary terrestrial component vs. a simple ground-based LTE service in the Mobile Satellite Service band, GPS receiver manufacturer Trimble Navigation Ltd. formed the "Coalition To Save Our GPS".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The FCC and LightSquared have each made public commitments to solve the GPS interference issue before the network is allowed to operate.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] According to Chris Dancy of the Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association, airline pilots with the type of systems that would be affected "may go off course and not even realize it".
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The problems could also affect the Federal Aviation Administration upgrade to the air traffic control system, United States Defense Department guidance, and local emergency services including 911.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] LightSquared is challenging the FCC's action.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] Following the United States's deployment of GPS, other countries have also developed their own satellite navigation systems.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] In the event of adverse space weather or the deployment of an anti-satellite weapon against GPS, the United States has no terrestrial backup system.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The potential cost of such an event to the U.S. economy is estimated at $1 billion per day.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] The LORAN-C system was turned off in North America in 2010 and Europe in 2015. eLoran is proposed as an American terrestrial backup system, but as of 2024 has not received approval or funding.
[src:geolocation-api/global-positioning-system-p02] China continues to operate LORAN-C transmitters, and Russia has a similar system called CHAYKA ("Seagull").
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] The **`watchPosition()`** method of the `Geolocation` interface is used to register a handler function that will be called automatically each time the position of the device changes.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] You can also, optionally, specify an error handling callback function.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] A callback function that takes a `GeolocationPosition` object as an input parameter.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] An optional callback function that takes a `GeolocationPositionError` object as an input parameter.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] An optional object that provides configuration options for the location watch.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] See `Geolocation.getCurrentPosition()` for more details on possible options.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] An integer ID that identifies the registered handler.
[src:geolocation-api/watchposition] The ID can be passed to the `Geolocation.clearWatch()` to unregister the handler.
